---
import ButtonBack from "../components/ButtonBack.astro";
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout title="Psyche Mission">
    <div class="w-full mb-0">
        <ButtonBack direction="/astro-spacex-clone/"/>
        <!-- Muestra la imagen de la pagina -->
        <div class="h-screen w-full">
          <div 
              class="w-full h-screen bg-no-repeat bg-cover bg-center flex justify-start items-center" 
              style="background-image: url(https://sxcontent9668.azureedge.us/cms-assets/assets/Psyche_outsidehangar_IMG_3705_desktop_0eaa6fdd97.jpg);">
          </div>
        </div>
        <!-- Se muestra la fecha y el titulo -->
        <div class="h-24 m-0 block relative py-0 -mt-52 ">
            <div class="text-left w-1/2 max-w-lg ml-12 mt-60">
                <p class="uppercase opacity-100 font-semibold m-0 mb-5 text-sm md:text-lg text-gray-500">October 17, 2023</p>
                <h1 class="m-auto font-bold text-lg md:text-2xl lg:text-4xl uppercase opacity-100">Psyche Mission</h1>
            </div>
        </div>
        <!-- Se muestra el contenido -->
        <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-5 px-12 py-0 my-8 w-auto">
            <div class="text-left mt-5 text-sm font-mono"
                style="flex-basis: 50%;"
            >
                <p class="lg:mt-5 -mt-12">
                    On Friday, October 13 at 10:19 a.m. ET, Falcon Heavy launched NASA's Psyche mission to an interplanetary transfer orbit from Launch Complex 39A (LC-39A) at Kennedy Space Center in Florida. This was the fourth launch for the side boosters, both of which previously supported the USSF-44, USSF-67, and Hughes JUPTER 3 missions.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="text-left mt-5 text-sm font-mono"
                style="flex-basis: 50%;"
            >
                <p class="lg:mt-5 md:-mt-12 sm:-mt-12 mt-0">
                    The Psyche spacecraft will travel to a metal-rich asteroid of the same name orbiting the Sun between Jupiter and Mars in pursuit of studying the exposed nickel-iron core of an early planet, one of the building blocks of our solar system. The mission will also demonstrate NASAâ€™s first deep space test of the Deep Space Optical Communications (DSOC) system high-bandwidth optical communications through space and back to Earth from distances far exceeding the Moon using a near-infrared laser.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</Layout>
